<HEADLINE> Iran Combats Drug Traffics at Great Cost: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iranian anti-drug official
said on Saturday that Iran pays a heavy price every year in combating
transit of narcotic drugs to Europe via Iranian territory, the Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of the Iranian anti-drug headquarters Mohammad Fallah
told a delegation from the International Narcotic Control Board (INCB)
that 80 Iranian policemen were killed and 200 others disabled in
anti-drug actions in the last Iranian calendar year (ended March 20).
</P>
<P>
Iran prevented transit of at least 25 tons of narcotic drugs to
Europe last Iranian year, Fallah said, adding that 195 tons of
different types of drugs have been seized across the country during
the year.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official said that Iran deployed 30,000 security
personnel on its eastern borders and the Iranian army and the
Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps also joined them recently.
</P>
<P>
He said some 8,000 foreign nationals are now held in Iranian
prisons for involvement in drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Head of the INCB delegation, whose name was not revealed, said that
the international community supports Iran in its anti-drug campaign.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the INCB can launch an effective cooperation with
Iran and that the international community would play an appropriate
role in anti-drug campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
