<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Makes 5.9 Bln Dlr Budget for Kosovo Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration has
worked out details of an emergency 5.9 billion dollar budget for
its operations in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The spending package will cover the cost of U.S. participation
in the NATO airstrikes and relief operation for refugees, AP
reported Saturday, quoting a senior government official who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration will formally present the request to
the Congress early next week, the official said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Defense Secretary William Cohen is expected
to ask President Clinton to approve the call-up of some 33,000
military reservists, including up to 25,000 Air National Guard
members in units that fly aerial refueling missions.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the
administration would probably ask for 3 billion to 4 billion
dollars for the Kosovo campaign.
</P>
<P>
Some members of Congress are reportedly pressing for spending
of from 10 billion dollars to 18 billion dollars to beef up the
armed forces in the military operation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. cost of the air war in Yugoslavia so far is likely to
be more than 2 billion dollars, perhaps far more, House
Appropriations Chairman Bill Young said.
</P>
<P>
"You know, you just can't go to war and take it out of petty
cash," he said.
</P>
<P>
Though the Pentagon has offered no cost estimates, an
independent research group estimated the cost of the war so far
at 450 million to 600 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The group says the costs will grow roughly half a billion
dollars every 10 days the air campaign continues, and will
explode if ground forces are deployed.
</P>
<P>
"You are looking at between 40 million and 55 million dollars
a day," said Leisl Heeter, analyst at the Center for Strategic
and Budgetary Assessments.
</P>
<P>
Cruise missiles run 1 million to 2 million dollars apiece,
depending on the type. The precise bombs dropped from warplanes
vary greatly in cost, from 6,000 dollars to 320,000 dollars each
while unguided munitions are from 300 dollars to 47,500 dollars
each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
