<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria not to Withdraw From S. Leone without </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian president-elect Olusegun
Obasanjo said Saturday that the west African peace-keeping troops
ECOMOG would not be withdrawn from Sierra Leone without adequate
security provisions for that country.
</P>
<P>
"Neither the head of state (General Abdulsalami Abubakar) nor
myself will withdraw troops without making sure that there are
sufficient and adequate security to safeguard smooth democratic
governance in that country," Olusegun emphasized, the Ghana News
Agency (GNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in Accra shortly before he left the
capital of Ghana for Lome, Togo on the last leg of his global
tour.
</P>
<P>
However, he intimated that ECOMOG, which is dominated by
Nigerian troops cannot remain in Sierra Leone forever, saying that
arrangements must be made for them to return home "sooner or
later."
</P>
<P>
The situation in Sierra Leone requires a permanent solution
and not military solutions, which he termed as "temporary
solutions".
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian president-elect said he has had the occasion to
consult with President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah who indicated that
something positive will be done to bring a lasting solution to the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo, who told journalists during his visit to Ghana last
September that he was not going to contest the elections, said he
reversed the decision to satisfy the will of his countrymen.
</P>
<P>
 "The people of Nigeria called on me as an experienced
statesman to intervene and reconstruct with reconciliation. You
may say never but cannot do otherwise if the people say ever."
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo who will take office next month said he does not
anticipate the problem of ethnicity as was with some past
governments because his victory cuts across ethnic boundaries.
</P>
<P>
Unlike most African leaders whose support come from their
tribe, he said, he was fortunate to have enjoyed a massive support
from outside his home province.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes he would sustain the balance. "The
support will continue to come through performance... by showing
that we are a government for all the people of Nigeria."
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Obasanjo and his entourage held talks with
Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings and met with traditional rulers.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
