<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. Leone Rebels to Hold Peace Talks with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Sierra leone rebels are expected to
hold peace talks with the government of President Tejan Kabbah in
a bid to end the nine-year civil war in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
Final preparations for the travel of jailed rebel leader Foday
Sankoh to Togo were ready Friday when the United Nations lifted
the travel ban on him, a day after the Sierra Leone Appeal Court
agreed to release him temporarily.
</P>
<P>
A Sierra Leonean government spokesman said Friday that Sankoh
would be flown to Togo Saturday accompanied by U.N.
representatives and was expected to consult his followers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Following the face-to-face meeting with his followers, Sankoh
would hold peace talks with the Kabbah government to try to bring
peace to the war- ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
The decision to release him and allow him to travel to Togo for
meeting with his supporters are described as the most important
step toward peace in the west African country for several years.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh has been in detention since he was picked up on arms
offenses in Nigeria in early 1997 and was sentenced to death last
October as his Revolutionary United Front (RUF) briefly shared
power with renegade army officers in Freetown between May 1997 and
February 1998.
</P>
<P>
The RUF invaded Freetown early last January, and some 6,000
people were reportedly killed in the ensuing violence between the
west African peace-keeping force ECOMOG and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Kabbah government welcomed the Appeal Court's decision, and
called Sankoh's travel to Togo "a mission of national importance"
and "another important milestone in the peace process" in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
Since the RUF took up arms in 1991, at least 20,000 people have
been killed in Sierra Leone where almost every infrastructure,
especially those outside the capital, has been crippled by the
war.
</P>
<P>
The Togo meeting is scheduled to be held in Kara, the birth
place of President Gnassingbe Eyadema, current chairman of the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), who is to host
the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The eventual meeting is seen as a crucial precursor to
full-scale peace talks between the rebels and the Kabbah
government, coming at a time when Sierra leone's security
situation is precarious.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said Thursday that Kambia on the border with
Guinea in the north was now free of rebels while the northern town
of Makeni, Sierra Leone's third largest city, remains a rebel
stronghold.
</P>
<P>
In the east, the sources said, rebels still control Kailahun
which is the main base of the rebel movement while the Freetown
peninsula remains in the hands of the ECOMOG troops.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigerian Chief of Defense Staff Air Marshal Al-Amin
Daggash announced in capital Abuja Thursday that the ECOMOG would
begin to pull its 15,000-strong troops out of Sierra leone later
this year.
</P>
<P>
Defense chiefs of countries with troops in Sierra Leone ended a
one-day extraordinary meeting in Abuja Thursday with a call on
ECOWAS members to support the on-going rebuilding of the Sierra
Leone armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's former army, which sided with the RUF, was
demobilized by ECOMOG last year when the latter reinstated the
democratically elected President Kabbah after he was overthrown by
the military junta.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to rebuild the army, 500 officer cadets have been
sent for training in Nigeria while the rest of the 5,000-strong
army is being trained locally by Nigerian and British officers.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the Kabbah government is desperate for a peace
pact with the rebels in the upcoming peace talks next week.
</P>
<P>
Unless the talks succeed, the capital city of Freetown could be
laid open within weeks to a new rebel assault, they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
