<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Holds Talks with Gaddafi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
held talks with his Libyan counterpart Muammar Gaddafi in the town
of Sirte in Libya Saturday evening on the Congo (K) crisis.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the President's Office said here that
the discussions focused on the situation in the Great Lakes
region, especially that in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
DRC President Laurent Kabila, who arrived at the Sirte air base
a few minutes before Museveni, also attended the talks.
</P>
<P>
This is the latest effort made toward ending the
eight-month-long war in the third largest African country.
</P>
<P>
Kabila had long refused to talk face to face with the Tutsi
rebels fighting to oust him before showing some willingness to do
so recently.
</P>
<P>
The Tutsi rebels, allegedly backed by Uganda and Rwanda, have
made some gains in the front line, exerting more pressure on the
Kabila administration.
</P>
<P>
Museveni, accompanied by State Minister of Defense Steven
Kavuma and State Minister of Regional Cooperation Amama Mbabazi,
left here for Libya Saturday morning for a short official visit to
the northern African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
