<HEADLINE> 4 Iraqi Civilians Killed in U.S., British Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The spokesman was quoted by the Iraqi News Agency as saying that 10
formations of enemy warplanes of F-14, F-15 and F-16 coming from
Turkish airspace violated northern Iraqi airspace from 12:35 local
time (0835 GMT) to 15:45 local time (1145 GMT) and attacked civilian
facilities as well as military sites.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi air defenses fired surface-to-air missiles at the enemy
planes, he added.
</P>
<P>
Enemy warplanes coming from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases also violated
Iraq's southern airspace earlier in the day, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, two Iraqi civilians were killed and nine others
injured when U.S. and British warplanes attacked civilian and military
targets in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's United States-British airstrikes against
Iraq, U.S. and British jets patrolling the no-fly zones in Iraq have
clashed with Iraqi air defenses almost on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed two no-fly zones in Iraq
following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of protecting the
Kurds in the north and the Shitte Muslims in the south from "Baghdad's
suppression."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has vowed to continue confronting any allied planes violating
its airspace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
