<HEADLINE> Congolese Rebels Walk Out of Lusaka Peace Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The consultative committee meeting
on the implementation of a cease-fire agreement in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) ended here Saturday morning with the
committee expressing disappointment at rebels' decision to walk
out of the talks.
</P>
<P>
According to a draft statement released by Zambia's State
House, delegates of the Congolese rebels fighting to topple
President Laurent Kabila who were attending the meeting for the
first time walked out of the talks.
</P>
<P>
The statement states that the delegates requested to hold
bilateral talks with the delegation from the DRC and that this
forms the only agenda item.
</P>
<P>
Their request was turned down by the chairman of the talks who
said the committee had no mandate to facilitate the talks within
that framework.
</P>
<P>
The statement further states that delegates from the DRC had
however agreed to hold a meeting with the rebels in a different
framework.
</P>
<P>
The meeting which started Thursday went ahead without the
rebels and the committee hoped that the rebels would be involved
in the peace process in future.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, both the rebels and the delegation from the Congolese
 government expressed their commitment to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Countries that sent representatives to the talks included
Angola, DRC, Namibia, Uganda and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from the Organization of African Unity (OAU) were
also present while Chad was represented by the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda, the Southern African Development Community (SADC) and
the United Nations were not represented at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The committee agreed to submit a report to the chairman of the
council of ministers on its deliberations on the draft document
regarding the modalities for the implementation of a cease-fire in
the DRC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
