<HEADLINE> Clark Arrives in Macedonian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- NATO Supreme Commander Wesley
Clark arrived Saturday morning in Skopje, capital of Macedonia, to
discuss the Kosovo crisis and issues related to NATO troops
stationed in the neighboring country of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for NATO troops in Macedonia, Verdock Dirk, was
quoted by the Albanian news agency ATA as saying that Clark had
requested meeting with Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov and
Prime Minister Ljubko Georgievski.
</P>
<P>
Clark will also meet with officers of the 12,000 NATO troops
currently stationed in Macedonia, which borders Kosovo, the
southern Serbian province of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia had maintained that it would not allow NATO troops to
launch a ground offensive against any of its neighboring countries
from its soil. But it said now it needed parliamentary approval to
allow foreign troops to enter Kosovo in case of a NATO ground
operation.
</P>
<P>
An Albanian Defense Ministry spokesman said that from Skopje,
Clark will travel to Tirana, capital of Albania, later Saturday to
meet with Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli Majko and Defense
Minister Luan Hajdaraga.
</P>
<P>
During his short stay here, the 54-year-old U.S. general was
also scheduled to visit NATO troops deployed in the military
airport in Rinas, Tirana and the NATO office in the capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
