<HEADLINE> Clark Pledges to Protect Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The NATO supreme commander, Wesley
Clark, said Saturday that the Western military alliance will give
protection to Albania and other neighboring countries of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. general made the pledge during his talks here Saturday
afternoon with Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli Majko.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters after the meeting that NATO will continue and
intensify its on-going air campaign against Yugoslavia and make
every effort to help maintain stability in Yugoslavia's
neighboring countries including Albania.
</P>
<P>
He accused Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic of threatening
security in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, it is a very important matter for
NATO to protect the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the
countries surrounding Yugoslavia, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
He said that NATO knew Yugoslavia has a plan to threaten
Albania and other countries and it will try every means to prevent
these countries from being attacked by Yugoslavia, which has been
subject to intensive NATO air strikes for more than three weeks
now.
</P>
<P>
Clark said that he discussed with Majko and Albanian Defense
Minister Luan Hajdaraga what he said the artillery shootings by
Serbian troops at northern Albania, especially the Serbian
infantry's threat against Albania.
</P>
<P>
He demanded that Yugoslavia halt these actions.
</P>
<P>
The NATO supreme commander said that NATO has two kinds of
forces in Albania -- one carrying out humanitarian tasks and the
other manning and supporting the Apache military helicopters,
which he said will arrive in Albania "very shortly."
</P>
<P>
Clark, who arrived here earlier Saturday from Skopje, capital
of Macedonia, also denied that NATO has made any coordination or
communication with the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA), which has
been fighting Serbian soldiers and paramilitary police for
independence.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia saw the KLA as a terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
During his short visit to Macedonia, Clark threatened to
destroy whatever Milosevic regards important to him if the
Yugoslav president does not change his current policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
