<HEADLINE> Simitis: Military Intervention Has Not Solved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis said here Saturday that military action by the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) against Yugoslavia has not
resolved the problems in Kosovo, but has made them worse.
</P>
<P>
"Military intervention has not solved problems. It has made
them worse and will not solve any problems in future," Simitis
said while addressing a meeting of his ruling Panhellenic
Socialist Movement (PASOK) Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Describing the developments in Kosovo as a potential threat to
peace and stability in the Balkan region, he said that Greece will
not participate in military operations against Belgrade and
stressed Athens' opposition to any act which may lead to a change
of existing borders.
</P>
<P>
The premier added that his government will continue its efforts
in seeking a political solution to the crisis not only at next
week's NATO summit in Washington but also through visits by Greek
ministers to other countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that the prolonged crisis in Kosovo has already had
repercussions for Greece by reducing this year's growth rate from
3.5 percent to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos said that
it is now time for political initiatives to bring an end to the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The European Union must work to safeguard the role of the
United Nations so that efforts to replace the U.N.'s role with a
new role for NATO do not bear fruit, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
