<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paris Club to Reduce Zambia's Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Paris Club meeting has agreed
to reduce and restructure a major part of Zambia's external debt,
the Zambia National Broadcasting Corporation reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a statement from the Paris Club meeting, which ended
Friday, as saying that the amount of debt to be treated under the
agreement is close to one billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of creditor countries also agreed to recommend
writing off 67 percent of debt service obligations due under
eligible loans and credits.
</P>
<P>
The other option will be a consolidation at concessionary rates
so as to reduce by 67 percent in net present value the payments
due on eligible loans and credits with a payment period of 33
years.
</P>
<P>
The representatives noted that Zambia's low per capita income
and heavy debt burden call for strong adjustment.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian delegation led by Finance Minister Edith Nawakwi
asked for a concessionary treatment of her country's debt.
</P>
<P>
Nawakwi said this will make resources available for the social
and development programs of the country. 
</P>
