<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Resumes Urgent Food Aid to W. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program (WFP)
</P>
<P>
announced here Saturday that it has resumed sending relief food
convoys to Western Uganda after a temporary halt to the operation
last week.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. food aid agency began dispatching food to the area 12
days ago, but had to suspended last week due to an increase in
attacks and ambushes on commercial transporters.
</P>
<P>
"We have been forced to arrange military escorts to accompany
our food convoys to ensure that transporters can travel safely and
the food reaches those who need it," said Michael Jones, WFP's
deputy country director for Uganda.
</P>
<P>
A convoy of trucks carrying 70 tons of WFP food supplies
arrived safely in Bundibugyo town in Western Uganda early this
week.
</P>
<P>
The aid agency estimated that 50,000 to 70,000 Ugandans living
in the Western district of Bundibugyo have become displaced over
the past four weeks.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the area indicate that Ugandan rebels from the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) have been violently attacking
villagers, killing people and burning houses before retreating to
the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"It is becoming increasing difficult to find transporters
willing to risk their lives to carry relief supplies to this
area," Jones said.
</P>
<P>
WFP is currently sending to the area a total consignment of 200
tons of maize, beans, oil and corn-soya blend, which will be
enough to feed 30,000 of the neediest people for one month.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of the food has now arrived in the area. The WFP
plans to send the remaining supplies over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
The WFP has been operational in Uganda for the past 35 years.
The agency also currently provides support to development projects
in the areas of education, vocational training, food security and
agricultural activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
