<DOCNO> XIE19990418.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Situation Much Improved in Singapore Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SINGAPORE April 17 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Minister for Home
Affairs Wong Kan Seng said here Saturday that the number of drug
abusers in Singapore has shrank significantly from its peak in
1994 as a result of efforts and measures undertaken by the
government.
</P>
<P>
Wong told a national seminar on drug abuse that the number of
heroin abusers fell by 37 percent in 1998 compared to 1994 when
6,165 of drug abusers were arrested.
</P>
<P>
New heroin abusers fell by even greater percentage, Wong said,
comparing the 428 abusers arrested in 1998 and the high of 1246 in
1994.
</P>
<P>
The relapse rate has fallen to 54 percent in 1998 from a high of
81 percent in 1994, Wong added.
</P>
<P>
Wong attributed the good results to tough law in tandem with
intensive enforcement efforts as well as to community involvement
</P>
<P>
One of the key ideas in the Singapore 21 vision, which Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong will be launching next week, is "Active
Citizenship", he said, adding that it is getting Singaporeans to
actively contribute their time and energy to build a better
Singapore and entails citizens taking ownership of society's
problems and sharing responsibility, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
The involvement of the community in drug prevention has paid
dividends, Wong Said, citing the Malay self-help groups have
managed to bring down the number of Malay heroin abusers by 36
percent from 3,209 in 1994 to 2,059 last year.
</P>
<P>
Wong also said one of the challenges Singapore is facing is the
fight against new drugs of abuse, in particular Amphetamines-Type
Stimulants or ATS such as "Ecstasy" and "Ice".
</P>
<P>
The number of "Ecstasy" abusers has decreased to 180 last year
from 661 in 1996 while "Ice" abusers increased from 5 in 1996 to
117 last year, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He urged harder work and closer cooperation in a bid to sustain
and extend the achievements made in the heroin situation to new
challenges ahead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
