<HEADLINE> Ghana Pledges Coop with Incoming Nigerian Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings
Saturday pledged Ghana's cooperation with the incoming Nigerian
government for the sustenance of peace and stability in the west
Africa sub-region.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that Nigerian president-elect Olusengu
Obasanjo would pay attention to the challenges facing the region,
notwithstanding domestic issues, the Ghana News Agency (GNA)
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"We do not live in isolation, therefore the peace and stability
of others in the region should be of equal concern to us,"
Rawlings said in his welcoming remarks for Obasanjo shortly before
they went into closed-door talks.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo arrived in Accra, Ghanaian capital, early Saturday
with a team of politicians and businessmen for a one-day visit as
part of his global tour.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings said it is necessary for leaders of the sub-region,
particularly those of Ghana and Nigeria, to provide the right
leadership to create the appropriate atmosphere to sustain
stability.
</P>
<P>
He commended Nigeria for its consistent commitment to the
challenges over the years, saying the country has never abdicated
its responsibility not only to its people but also to the entire
continent.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings congratulated Obasanjo, who will assume office next
month, for winning the honor and confidence of his people.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that he is assuming the mantle with a
great deal of goodwill and determination to overcome the
complexities that go with it in order to build on the foundation
laid by General Abdusalami Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said he has always ''regarded Ghana as a true friend
and a brother of Nigeria,'' hence the visit.
</P>
<P>
"My visit is a friendly one and a goodwill one to a brother,"
he told Rawlings, adding that he decided to visit Ghana before he
assumes the hectic office.
</P>
<P>
He said he credits every opportunity he has had in life to
Ghana as his "beginning place''.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo commended the government and people of Ghana for
supporting his country throughout its (Nigeria's) turbulent
period.
</P>
<P>
He also praised Ghana's leadership role in the search for
peace and stability in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said while in Ghana, he would discuss bilateral and
multi- lateral issues with the authorities.
</P>
<P>
James Victor Gbeho, Minister of Foreign Affairs, expressed the
hope that consultations with the president-elect will boost
efforts of Ghana and Nigeria for the advancement of the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo and his entourage will meet with the Nigerian
community in Accra before leaving for Lome, Togo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
