<HEADLINE> Iran, Yemen Call for Expansion of Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi and his Yemeni counterpart Abdul Qader Ba-Jammal on
Saturday called for further expansion of bilateral ties and
cooperation in their first round of talks.
</P>
<P>
Ba-Jammal, who arrived here on Saturday morning for a three-day
official visit, said that the political systems in Yemen and Iran, the
peoples' increasing role in the economic, political and cultural
arenas and their commonalties are grounds for further expansion of
mutual cooperation and understanding between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that Yemen's foreign policy is based on maintaining good
relations with neighbors and establishing peace and stability in the
region, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Tehran-Sana relations and regional cooperation
between the two sides would be upgraded in light of their religious
and historical commonalties.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that the Gulf is a highly sensitive and strategic
region and that Iran strongly believes security and stability in the
region should be preserved by regional states.
</P>
<P>
Detente, confidence-building and cooperation among regional states
have been given priority in Iran's foreign policy, the Iranian
minister said, adding that exchange of talks among regional states
would foil conspiracies of those who are against friendship among
regional nations.
</P>
<P>
Calling for efforts to ease tensions and hold dialogs, he said
that good relations among regional states would help the peace
process, stability and economic development in the region.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also exchanged views on a future visit of Yemeni
President Ali Abdullah Saleh to Tehran, the fourth Tehran-Sana joint
economic commission and mutual cooperation in oil, fisheries, cultural
and academic fields. 
</P>
