<HEADLINE> NATO Says No Fresh Information On Incidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A NATO spokesman said here
Saturday that no further information about the bombing tragedy of
civilian convoys could be provided so far as related investigation
is still going on.
</P>
<P>
NATO civilian spokesman Jamie Shea told reporters that he had,
during the last 24 hours, received no new information on the
convoy incidents.
</P>
<P>
"I'v made clear that if I have fresh information, I will pass
it on. But the investigation to put the effects on the table
continues. So that is the best and most honest answer that I can
give you."
</P>
<P>
However, a journalist still asked "quite simply questions"
about how many attacks that NATO plains made on the road west of
Djakovica Wednesday and how many bombs they dropped, he also asked
how many Yugoslav fielded forces and armored forces in Kosovo have
been damaged by NATO forces. NATO military spokesman Giuseppe
Marani said the answer is no for both questions. "I cannot tell,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Shea explained that military commanders will be going to make
overall assessment in the next few days "as we begin to prepare
for the Washington summit."
</P>
<P>
"So once the assessment had been put together, obviously we'll
share the result with you that we can share, that exercise is on
going and will be submitted to the NATO ambassadors in the course
of the week before they leave on Thursday for Washington," Shea
told a daily news briefing at NATO headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Usually, NATO gives relatively detailed information about the
development of air strikes against Yugoslavia. But many
journalists here were frustrated by NATO's reluctance to provide
information on the attack on civilian convoys, in which more than
70 civilian Albanian refugees were reportedly killed by NATO's
laser-guided missiles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
