<HEADLINE> Cypriot Party to Help Yugoslavs in International Fora </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The main opposition party in Cyprus
Saturday expressed its willingness to speak on behalf of Yugoslavia in
international fora.
</P>
<P>
Two parliament deputies of Cyprus' Progressive Party of Working
People (AKEL), Nicos Katsourides and Doros Christodoulides, held a
press conference Saturday on their two-day visit in Belgrade earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
AKEL, winning 33 percent of the votes in the 1996 parliamentary
elections, is the main opposition left-wing party in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Katsoulides, also AKEL spokesman, said Yugoslav Foreign Minister
Zivadin Jovanovic told them his government is willing to accept a
"political, peaceful settlement" by conceding Kosovo self-government
that will take into consideration the rights and interests of all
ethnic groups living in the region.
</P>
<P>
It is also ready to accept the presence of political observers
during peace negotiations on condition that they are not from member
countries of the North Atlantic Treaty Organizations (NATO), he said.
</P>
<P>
NATO started its air strikes against Yugoslavia last month to
punish what they called Belgrade's refusal to accept a peace deal
with the independent-seeking Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Katsoulides said the Yugoslav government re-asserted it will not
accept foreign military presence in the country, a stance that has led
to the collapse of its peace talks with Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav people consider the ongoing NATO attacks against their
country is only a beginning and the Western military bloc will
also target other nations in the future, the AKEL deputy said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Yugoslavs do not rule out the possibility of a
NATO ground operation in their country soon and believe that such a
move would lead to an overall conflict in the region.
</P>
<P>
"If a land operation begins, they believe that the hostilities will
last for years," Katsoulides noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
