<HEADLINE> Iranian President Urged to Protect Journalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Over 320 Iranian journalists on
Saturday urged President Mohammad Khatami to protect journalists in
the country after a moderate daily was closed down by the conservative
revolutionary court.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Khatami, the journalists called on the Iranian
president to provide special legal services and protection to
journalists and to investigate press violations in accordance with the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Iranian revolutionary court ordered to
close down the daily Zan (Women) until further notice for publishing a
letter of Farah Diba, the ousted Iranian queen and a caricature making
fun of "blood money" -- a compensation paid by killers to the victim's
family.
</P>
<P>
However, Managing Director of the moderate Persian-language daily
Faezeh Hashemi, daughter of former Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani, rejected the accusation that the publication of Farah's
message on March 21, the begining of the new Iranian year, was
publicity for the former Iranian shah regime.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the closure of the daily was a political campaign
initiated by the hard-line conservatives against the moderates, the
main supporters of President Khatami's open-minded policies.
</P>
<P>
The journalists said in their letter that the ban on the Zan
newspaper by the revolutionary court violated Article 168 of the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, press violations should be looked into in
an open court session and in the presence of a jury, the Islamic
Republic News Agency quoted the letter as saying.
</P>
<P>
They called for an immediate end to "illogical and illegal methods"
in dealing with the press and asked Khatami to clearly define the
categories of press violations so as to prevent anyone taking
advantages of the ambiguities in the definition.
</P>
<P>
This will safeguard the independence, freedom and diversity of the
press, they pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Eight newspapers and weeklies were forced to close in the past year
and two other publications were on the verge of closure, the letter
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
