<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Finance Ministers to Reform Economic Structures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The finance ministers of the 15
European Union (EU) members Saturday called for a push to create
new frameworks for dealing with the economic problems in Europe
and to strengthen the financial systems for confronting the global
market turbulence.
</P>
<P>
The ministers attending a two-day informal meeting in Dresden,
Germany, sketched up a new structure that would draw governments,
the European Central Bank (ECB) and the unions together to solve
the common European economic problems, notably the high
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministers are considering a report for steps
aimed at avoiding the turmoil that recently hit the world money
markets, officials said. The report was issued by Hans Tietmeyer,
president of the German central bank Bundesbank.
</P>
<P>
Wim Duisenberg, president of the ECB, together with heads of
the EU's 15 national central banks, also attended the meeting
chaired by the new German Finance Minister Hans Eichel.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was not expected to make any decisions and was
aimed at building the foundation for the EU leaders' meeting and
the summit of the Group of Seven (G7) in the next months.
</P>
<P>
With this goal ahead, the ministers took a further step toward
the creation of a jobs pact and the moves to ensure closer
consultations between Europe's monetary authorities, national
governments and the social partners.
</P>
<P>
The proposed increased economic coordination would not hurt the
independence of the ECB, Eichel and Duisenberg ensured.
</P>
<P>
The ECB would not cooperate with any proposals which might
impinge on its performance, Duisenberg said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the success in promoting economic structure reform,
there were few signs at the Dresden meeting that any compromise
had been made on controversial plans of imposing a Europe-wide
saving tax cut with Britain and Luxembourg in opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
