<HEADLINE> Nearly 50 Injured in London Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Some 50 people were injured in a
bomb blast in a busy shopping street in south London Saturday,
police said.
</P>
<P>
There was no warning before the bomb exploded around 5.30 p.m.
(1630 GMT) near an Iceland supermarket in Brixton.
</P>
<P>
Commander Hugh Ord told reporters 48 people were taken to three
hospitals for treatment, including a police officer. Two of the
victims, one of them a child, were seriously injured, he added.
</P>
<P>
"There was no warning from any of our recognized sources and it
is too early to speculate about the nature of the bomb," Ord said.
</P>
<P>
Shops and flats near the Iceland supermarket were damaged and
glass was scattered over a wide area.
</P>
<P>
One witness said the explosion happened when a boy moved a bag
that had been left between market stalls. The boy was said to have
suffered only minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
No one has claimed responsibility for the blast so far.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the New Scotland Yard said the bomb did not seem to be
related to any of the terrorist groups in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Home Office Secretary Jack Straw condemned the blast.
</P>
<P>
"This is an outrageous and mindless act. Our sympathies go out
to those injured and their families and the family of the injured
police officer," he said in a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
