<HEADLINE>   Chen Hua loses in Chinese National Swimmig Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAQING, Northeast China, April 18 (Xinhua) -- China's Asia
Games champion Chen Hua walked out of the swimming pool empty-
handed on Sunday for the first time since the Chinese national
swimming champions meet opened on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old native in east China's Zhejiang Province and
triple gold-medalist from last December's Bangkok Games had had
two titles from the first two days of the four-day event, which
also serves as a qualifier for the National Cities Games in
September.
</P>
<P>
But in Chen's speciality event of the women's 400 meters
freestyle Sunday night, Qin Caini representing southern Chinese
city of Guangzhou edged Chen by 34 hundredths of a second,
clocking four minutes 13.51 seconds to Chen's 4:13.85.
</P>
<P>
Although Qin's time was slower than her personal best, her
coach Wu Jicai looked happy. "It's obviously not her best
performance, probably because she has had various competitions
ever since the Asian Games. Her triumph was much owed to Chen's
sub-par performance," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Chen Hua competed too much in recent months and is really
exhaulsted. What else can I ask for her?" said her coach Zhu
Zhigen.
</P>
<P>
Men's 200m breaststroke final was widely open, as predicted by
Chen Yunpeng, former head coach of China's national team, after a
surprisingly poor show in this morning's heats cost Asian Games
champion Zhu Yi's chance for the finals. Tao Rong, a fairly
unknown from Zhejiang Province took the title in 2:18.73.
</P>
<P>
Xie Xufeng from Guangdong, silver-medalist from the Asian Games
in Bangkok, won his specialist event of the men's 200m butterfly
in 2:01.09, which is 2.02 seconds slower than his national record.
</P>
<P>
Deng Qingsong from Heibei Province, 22, won the men's 100m
freestyle in 51.97 seconds. The event's Asian and Chinese national
record is 50.51, still held by Chinese Shen Jianqiang.
</P>
<P>
Pang Ran, a 18-year-old Beijing native but competing here for
central Chinese city of Wuhan, won the women's 100m butterfly in 1:
00.34, beating Asian Games silver-medalist Ruan Yi to second. Ruan,
ranked 17th in the world last year for the 100m event, won the 200
m butterfly on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Asian Games champion Li Wei of a Shanghai native but entered
the event here in individual status, won the women's 100m
breaststroke in 1:01.03, much slower than her 1998 personal best
and seventh-ranked time of 1:08.76.
</P>
<P>
And a Wuhan city team completely formed with Beijing-native
swimmers won the day's only team event women's 4x100m freestyle
relay in 3:51.07. The swimmers are competing in the champions meet
since Beijing, as a municipality under central administration, is
not eligible for the Cities Games.
</P>
<P>
The national champions meet closes after eight more finals
Monday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
