<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bridge Given Government Green Light </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- China's longest suspension
bridge, the Humen Bridge over the Pearl River in Guangdong
Province in south China, which opened to traffic on a trial basis
two years ago, has been inspected and given the official green
light by the government.
</P>
<P>
Completion of the bridge, with a total length of 15.76
kilometers and a center span of 888 meters, and at a cost of 3.6
billion yuan (about 361 million US dollars), indicates that
China's bridge building technology has entered a new level, said
experts.
</P>
<P>
The bridge shortens the distance between the special economic
zones of Shenzhen and Zhuhai by 100 km., and will boost economic
development in the Pearl River Delta and prosperity in Hong Kong
and Macao. 
</P>
