<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Hopes Pakistan, India Solve Disputes Through Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 18 (Xinhua) -- China always hopes that Pakistan
and India can solve their disputes through peaceful negotiations
instead of resorting to force, Li Peng, China's top legislator,
said here late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
China does not want to see an arms race between the two
countries, since it is not in the interests of the peoples in the
South Asian region and is by no means conducive to the peace,
stability and development of the region, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li, Chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress of China (NPC), made the remarks at a press conference
held on the eve of the ending of his six-nation tour, which has
brought him to Greece, Turkey, Syria, Pakistan and Bangladesh
before Thailand.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the medium-range missile India launched on
April is directed against China and how China deal with its
relations with Pakistan and India, Li said China holds peaceful
diplomatic policies of independence and self-reliance and
maintains good relations with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Helping each other whenever needed, China and Pakistan enjoy
time-tested friendship. "We are friends of all weathers," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China and India share a long border line, on which
the two countries have some disputes.
</P>
<P>
But bilateral relations between China and India have improved
since both sides made common efforts so that agreements could be
signed to guarantee peace in the border area.
</P>
<P>
As for the nuclear issue, Li said though China is a country
with nuclear weapons, it firmly sticks to the commitment not to
conduct further nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
China is very much concerned on the nuclear tests conducted by
India and Pakistan last year, which aggravated the tension in
South Asia.
</P>
<P>
"We noticed that in both cases it was India that conducted
nuclear tests and launched medium-range missile first before
Pakistan followed suit," Li said.
</P>
<P>
China welcomes the recent meeting between Indian and Pakistani
prime ministers in Lahore, Pakistan, at which the two prime
ministers expressed their willingness to solve all their disputes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
