<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Staff Return to Afghan City of Kandahar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 18 (Xinhua) -- An eight-member team of U.N.
international staff Sunday returned to the southern Afghan city of
Kandahar, the stronghold of the Taliban militia, to monitor relief
activities.
</P>
<P>
The News Network International quoted Stephanie Bunker, a U.N.
official here, as saying that the team will stay in Kandahar till
Wednesday (April 21) and will hold meetings with the local U.N.
staff and non-governmental organizations about the relief
operations there.
</P>
<P>
All U.N. international workers were pulled out of war-torn
Afghanistan in August last year following killings of three U.N.
staff including two local workers and an Italian military
official.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and the Taliban signed a security agreement
for the return of the U.N. international staff in October last
year. Under the agreement, the Taliban are asked to provide
protection to the U.N. staff, its premises and to investigate into
the killings of the three U.N. staff members.
</P>
<P>
In March this year, the U.N. announced plans to gradually send
humanitarian workers back to Afghanistan after reaching an
agreement with the Taliban to ensure safety and security of the
U.N. international and national staff.
</P>
<P>
Bunker said that the next team of the U.N. international staff
will proceed to the eastern Afghan city of Jalalabad shortly to
review relief activities there.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan said last week that he would
consider withdrawal of the U.N. staff from Afghanistan for the
second time if the Taliban leadership does not ensure their
safety.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.N. sources here said that the U.N. World Food
Program also plans to resume its relief operations in the northern
Afghan town of Mazar-i-Sharif, which it left in 1997 after massive
looting of its food stocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
