<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   African Runners Dominate London Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Abdelkader El Mouaziz of Morocco
produced a superb display of front-running to win the London
Marathon in two hours seven minutes and 57 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a gritty little Joyce Chepchumba of Kenya grabbed
the second victory in her marathon career in the women's race with
a course record time of two hours 22 minutes and 21 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Behind the elite runnners, a race-record total of 31,582 took
part in the 19th running of the gruelling race around central
London in a sunny but cold day.
</P>
<P>
El Mouaziz improved on his second place last year to cross the
finish line in the Mall in two hours, seven minutes and 57 seconds.
</P>
<P>
With more than 14 kilometers to finish, the Moroccan began to
make a break and his gamble looked to have paid off as he forged a
two-minute lead over an illustrious pack.
</P>
<P>
But two-time champion Antonio Pinto of Portugal staged an
amazing late bid for victory, powering over the final stretches in
pursuit of the leader.
</P>
<P>
The gap proved too much for course record-holder Pinto, however,
as Mouaziz held on to win.
</P>
<P>
"After finishing the first half, I knew I was in the leading
group and I was almost sure at the moment that I will win," said
the Moroccan, who looked very tired at the finishing stage.
</P>
<P>
Abel Anton of Spain finished third at 2:09:41.
</P>
<P>
Josia Thugwane, the first black runner from South Africa to win
a gold medal at the Atlanta Olympic Games, was forced to drop out
after 35 kilometers due to bad chest and Kenyan Esther Kiplagat
retired after starting off of the cold weather.
</P>
<P>
In the women's race, Chepchumba, who was third last year having
won in 1997, secured 125,000 U.S. dollars for running the "world
best time", after bettering the previous best by one second.
</P>
<P>
"I did not know it was a world best, but now I believe it," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan will collect a total of 235,000 U.S. dollars from
the race, according to organizers.
</P>
<P>
She shaved just three seconds of Romanian Lidia Simon's mark of
2:23:24, which the London organizers consider to be the world
record.
</P>
<P>
They had refused to recognize the official world best of 2:20.
47, clocked by Chepchumba's compatriot Teglas Loroupe in Rotterdam
last year, because it was set in a mixed race.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is better to run in women's only race," said the
Kenyan, who increased her speed after about 25 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
"But I had some problem with my stomach then, " she said.
</P>
<P>
Chepchumba was involved in an early tussle for the lead with a
group including favorite Elana Meyer of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Adriana Fernandez of Mexico then moved ahead of the field going
into the final stages - but Chepchumba forced her way to the front
three miles from home and never looked like being caught.
</P>
<P>
Fernandez was second in 2:24:06 with Manuela Machado of
Portugal third at 2:25:08.
</P>
<P>
Heinz Frei of Switzerland won the men's wheelchair event for
the third time. He missed out on his own London record by seven
seconds but held off a determined challenge in the final stretch
to secure another victory.
</P>
<P>
And Monica Wedderstrom secured the spoils in the women's
wheelchair race for the second time.
</P>
<P>
She failed to improve on her course record but was well clear
of the field, with four times winner Tanni Grey of Britain
finishing in second spot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
