<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Steps up Construction of Gas Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to ease the increasingly
acute energy shortage in the Yangtze River Delta, which is a
direct result of the rapid economic development, the China
National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) has announced that it is
stepping up efforts to build a 55 billion yuan gas pipeline
between Xinjiang and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The 4,200-kilometer pipeline, which will run through 10
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions, will be
completed in the year 2007, Shi Xingquan, assistant general
manager of CNPC, revealed here today.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the pipeline in the western part of the project
has been finished while it is estimated that it will cost a
further 100 billion yuan to build the eastern sections.
</P>
<P>
Once completed CNPC and the Chinese government believe it will
form a new growth point for local economic development and will
certainly boost the development of iron, steel, cement, machine-
building, electronics and the building industries in central and
western China.
</P>
<P>
Gas consumption in western China is negligible although it has
abundant oil and gas resources with proven gas reserves in the
area amounting to 1.5 trillion cubic meters. Annual gas production
capacity has already reached 18 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, the central government has invested
heavily in the exploration of such resources in the area in a bid
to narrow the economic gap between eastern and western parts of
China. Gas will also play a major part in China's 21st century
plans to reduce the high pollution levels in its major cities and
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
To date four big gas fields have been discovered in China and
are fully operational in terms of extraction. They are located in
the Tarim and Qaidam basins, the Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia region and
in eastern Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
According to CNPC, the Yangtze River Delta's annual demand for
gas is expected to reach 12 billion cubic meters within the next
five years. It says that with the completion of the pipeline, the
four fields will reportedly be able to supply 25 billion cubic
meters of gas a year to the Delta, much higher than its present
and near future needs, with the reserves calculated to last 30
years.
</P>
<P>
In the Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia region, gas reserves totaling 230
billion cubic meters have already been verified while in Sichuan
there is a further 200 billion cubic meters. Total gas reserves of
160 billion cubic meters have also been verified in the Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
The State has approved construction of over 30 large gas
related projects in these areas as well as eight natural gas and
petrochemical bases which are variously located in Urumqi and
Yinchuan, the capitals of Xinjiang and Ningxia, and in Yulin in
Shaanxi.
</P>
<P>
The government is also keen that this project will also
encourage the industrialization and urbanization of western China
and help improve the environment and economies of medium-sized and
small cities in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990418.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
