<HEADLINE> Forest Fire in Sichuan Province Put out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Sterling efforts by more than 1,
000 firefighters have successfully put out a major forest fire in
southwest China's Sichuan Province that broke out on April 13 and
was finally extinguished this morning.
</P>
<P>
There were no reports of casualties and the cause of the fire
is as yet unknown.
</P>
<P>
The fire, in forests in the Muli Tibetan Autonomous County,
about 500 kilometers southwest of Chengdu, the provincial capital,
is the third in the area this year and spread over nearly 100
hectares, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Shengxian, vice-director of the State Administration of
Forestry, said that the recent spate of forest fires in Sichuan
have attracted the close attention of local officials and were put
out in a short time to minimize the economic loss.
</P>
<P>
The forest fire, 3,300 meters above sea level, was first
spotted by a local aircraft on April 13, and local officials and
firefighters rushed to the scene, but poor transport
infrastructure made the logistics and movement of supplies
extremely difficult and the dry weather and very low humidity made
things even worse, according to official sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
