<HEADLINE> Israel Accuses PNA of Intervention in Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu accused the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Sunday of
intervening in Israel's upcoming elections in May by trying to
influence Israeli Arab voters and candidates.
</P>
<P>
At a weekly plenary session of the cabinet, Netanyahu confirmed
remarks made earlier in the day by Amos Malka, head of the military
intelligence, who said the intervention was "incendiary."
</P>
<P>
But Malka, who made the accusation while briefing an inner cabinet
meeting, refused to discuss the matter at the full cabinet session,
saying it is "too sensitive," according to Israel Radio reports.
</P>
<P>
The radio said PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat has been reportedly
trying to persuade Azmi Bishara, Arab legislator in the Israeli
parliament as well as head of the National Democratic Alliance, to
drop his candidacy for the next Israeli premiership.
</P>
<P>
Arafat feared that Bishara's participation in the race would harm the
chances of other pro-peace candidates, such as One Israel alliance
leader Ehud Barak and Center Party leader Yitzhak Mordechai, by taking
away their votes, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Accounting for 18 percent of Israel's population, Israeli Arabs
have become a key voting bloc in the May 17 elections.
</P>
<P>
As the first-ever Arab running for the top government office in
Israel, Bishara admits that he has a very slim chance of being
elected.
</P>
<P>
He said he joined the race only in order to draw attention to
issues important to the Arab communities.
</P>
<P>
But he has been criticized by other Arab parties competing in the
elections, including the United Arab List, which holds four seats in
the current Knesset (parliament), for splitting the Arab votes.
</P>
<P>
They said the division of Arab votes would not only hamper Arab
parties in Knesset elections but also eventually narrow the chances of
moderate candidates for prime ministership to beat hard-line
Netanyahu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
