<HEADLINE> Chissano Confirms Intention for Next Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano has confirmed his intention to run for the next
presidency in the coming presidential and parliamentary elections
this October.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the weekly newspaper Domingo which
publishes on Sunday, Chissano said Saturday that "I know that some
members in the ruling Mozambican Liberation Front are trying to
choose me as the candidate for the second term, though the party
has not declare such withes".
</P>
<P>
Chissano said that he could not refuse the wishes of the party,
saying that it is evading his responsibility if he refuse to run
in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
On the question of postponing the elections to 2000, Chissano
said that his government believes that it should be held within
this year, adding that the national electoral commission is
preparing for the elections.
</P>
<P>
The African affair section of the Association of European
Parliamentary Members said in a recent report that Mozambique
faces a lot of difficulties, like the voters' registration and the
approaching of rainy season which may bring difficulty to the
elections, though theoretically the election is feasible in
October.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the voters' registration time would have
to be reduced to 60 days from the planned 75 days, and the
campaign reduced to 30 days from 45 days if the election is to be
held this year.
</P>
<P>
If this is the case, the report said, that the election would
have to be held in mid-December which marks the start of the rainy
season, which is to last till March.
</P>
<P>
It is also worried that some scandal within the European Union
may impact its timely financial aid to Mozambique for the
election.
</P>
<P>
The election in Mozambique needs 42 million U.S. dollars, of
which 21 million is to be offered by EU.  
</P>
