<HEADLINE> May 4th Photo Exhibition Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming 80th anniversary
of the historically significant May 4th Movement was given an
early boost today by the opening of a photo exhibition in the
Museum of the Chinese Revolution which will last until April 23.
</P>
<P>
The May 4th Movement began in 1919 and was organized by
university students in Beijing and other cities to protest against
the post First World War Versailles peace conference decision to
grant Japan the right to take over the special privileges enjoyed
by Germany and China's acceptance of that controversial decision.
</P>
<P>
The movement is considered to be a landmark in China with
university students and the intelligentsia demanding democracy for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
Sponsored by the Xinhua News Agency and the Communist Youth
League of China (CYLC) Central Committee, 220 photos selected from
the rich historical archives are on display in the exhibition,
which also commemorates China's ongoing 80 years of struggle for
democracy and freedom.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 students from Beijing University, Qinghua
University, Beijing Normal University and China Youth Political
College and other young delegates attended today's opening
ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
