<HEADLINE> Chinese Radio Awards Nepalese Winners of Knowledge Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- China Radio International (CRI)
awarded here Sunday prizes to 125 Nepalese winners of a knowledge
contest on the '99 International Horticulture Exposition to be
opened on May 1 in Kunming, Yunnan Province of Southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Zou Zhaojun, chief of the CRI's Nepali section, gave away 20
first prizes, 40 second prizes and 65 third prizes at a function
organized by the National Council of CRI Listeners Clubs Nepal.
</P>
<P>
She said that CRI received more than 50,000 answer sheets; the
radio organizes such contests one or two times every year for its
Nepalese listeners.
</P>
<P>
The Nepalese listeners show keen interest in the contest
program.
</P>
<P>
"I take part in every competition of CRI," said Nagendra
Pahadi, who was elected Saturday general secretary of the National
Council of CRI Listeners Clubs Nepal at the second national
convention of the clubs.
</P>
<P>
He won a first prize in the knowledge contest on the Kunming
horticulture exposition. "This contest gives information on how
China protects the minority groups. China has made great efforts
to protect the minority groups," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he wrote an 11-page book entitled "Kunming through
the Eye of a Nepali"; the handwritten book has been sent to
Kunming via CRI.
</P>
<P>
A student of sociology at the Tribhuvan University, Pahadi
began to tune to CRI in 1984 when he was only 7 years old. He also
reads Chinese magazines like China Today and Beijing Review. He
said that comparatively he has a good knowledge about China.
</P>
<P>
He was among the three Nepalese winning a China Today reading
contest in 1998. He said he has won first prize four times, second
prize two times and third prize one time.
</P>
<P>
Bishwa Rai, who works for a non-governmental organization in
Baglung district of western Nepal, tuned to CRI last year and he
won a first prize in the knowledge contest on the Kunming
floriculture exposition.
</P>
<P>
He said he likes most the current events survey program which
follows the news.
</P>
<P>
CRI began its Nepali service on June 25, 1975. Currently it is
broadcasting one-hour programs every day including news about
China and the world, current events survey and special topics.
</P>
<P>
There are 450 CRI listeners clubs in the kingdom with an
estimated 50,000 listeners.
</P>
<P>
Prakash Babu Poudel, president of the National Council of CRI
Listeners Clubs Nepal, told Xinhua that the council was
established on May 18, 1996 with a view to promoting friendship
between Nepal and China at the people's level.
</P>
<P>
He said that "We're good friends of China, we want to extend
our solidarity with its modernization process."
</P>
<P>
The president said on the occasion of Chinese national holidays
and other important occasions like the return of Hong Kong to the
motherland, his organization organizes celebration programs.
</P>
<P>
He said on the occasion of the 50th anniversary of the founding
of the People's Republic of China, the national council of the
listeners clubs plans to organize with CRI an essay competition
about China among the listeners.
</P>
<P>
The first three winners will be invited to visit China. "The
program is under discussion," he said.
</P>
<P>
The national council also intends to organize a special program
on the occasion of the 25th opening anniversary of CRI's Nepali
service.
</P>
<P>
"It's very important, it's in Nepali, people can get direct
information about international news, Chinese culture and China's
modernization process," Poudel said.
</P>
<P>
"We really appreciate the efforts of CRI," he added. 
</P>
