<HEADLINE> Kenyan Manufacturers Urge Govt to End Cheap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Association of
Manufacturers (KAM) has warned its government that the economy
cannot grow fast due to the dumping of cheap imports.
</P>
<P>
"By encouraging the importation of second-hand cars, another
name for dumping, the government has succeed in destroying the
domestic assembly plants," said KAM chairman Chris Kirubi.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Sunday quoted Kirubi as
saying that when these facts are ignored, a vicious chain
reaction is triggered off and ends up with the current state of
infrastructure and stunted growth.
</P>
<P>
"The Kenyan economy has an expansion base that can only be made
possible by strengthening the agriculture sector," said Kirubi on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He warned that there was no way Kenya would realize its 2020
industrialization goal if Kenya continued to import cheap
products.
</P>
<P>
Kirubi also noted that most products such as eggs, butter,
milk, juices, tomatoes and oranges are imported from South
Africa, New Zealand and the Far East, which are cheap due to
subsidies provided by their governments.
</P>
<P>
"The cheap imports only benefit a minority of Kenyans, and the
 government should concentrate on the manufacturing industry by
promoting sugar, cotton and rice farming that could benefit many
Kenyans by creating employment," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
