<HEADLINE> Mbeki Rules out Referendum on Death Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki Sunday ruled out a referendum on the death
penalty, saying the majority of people in the country supporting
the ruling African National Congress' (ANC) stand against capital
punishment.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed live on an E-TV Phone-In Program, Mbeki, who is ANC
chairman and set to become the country's new president in June,
said that his government would not entertain the idea of a
referendum.
</P>
<P>
"As the ANC, we are opposed to the death penalty. We believe
that this society is so violent. Levels of violence in South
Africa really horrible... It would be incorrect for the government
to join that process of encouraging the killing of people.
</P>
<P>
"I am quite sure that the majority of the people in this
country will support the ANC and they'll vote for the ANC," Mbeki
said.
</P>
<P>
The deputy president said there was no proof in terms of South
African history that the death penalty was in fact a deterrent
against crime.
</P>
<P>
"Tens of thousands of black people were hanged in this country.
it did not do anything to reduce levels of that sort of crime."
</P>
<P>
Apartheid and death penalty were abolished in 1994.
</P>
<P>
On whether the ANC government would do anything radically
different to combat crime, Mbeki spoke about toughening some
legislation, including the country's gun laws.
</P>
<P>
The illegal possession of firearms, for example, ought to be
punished with very heavy sentences, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
