<HEADLINE> Iranian President Blasts Armed Opposition Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
on Sunday lashed out at the Iranian outlawed Mujahideen Khalq
Organization (MKO) for asassinating deputy chief of the joint staff
of the armed forces Brigadier General Ali Sayyad Shirazi.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony at the Azadi Square to mark the Army Day,
Khatami said that the wicked remnants of the same groups, which
could not stand dignity of the people in the early days of the
victory of the Islamic revolution, again proved their grudge against
the people and the army by assassinating Shirazi.
</P>
<P>
Shirazi was assassinated on April 10 by the MKO members in front
of his home in northern Tehran. The iraq-based MKO also announced
responsibility for the killings.
</P>
<P>
The MKO was a famous armed group which fought against the former
Iranian shah regime before the islamic revolution in 1979, but it was
outlawed in 1981 following sharp differences with Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
Following khatami's speech, various units of the iranian armed
forces staged a parade at the square while air force parachutists
performed acrobatic operations in the air.
</P>
<P>
the Iranian army put on display its tanks and personnel carriers
designed and manufactured by Iranian specialists. However, it did
not show the missiles claimed to be developed by Iranian experts.
</P>
<P>
Iran said on Wednesday that it had "successfully" tested a
ground-to-air missile named after Sayyad Shirazi. Last July, it
test-fired the Shahab-3 (Metero-3) missile with a range of 1,300
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The test-fires have caused grave concerns of the United States
and Israel about Iran's military capabilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
