<HEADLINE> ICRC Representatives Visit Yugoslav POW Captured in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ICRC delegates held a private talk with him and registered
his personal details in order to notify the Yugoslav authorities,
the ICRC said in a press release. The prisoner wrote a Red Cross
Message which the ICRC will forward to his family.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to visit him while he is being held," said
ICRC spokesman Nicholas Sommer.
</P>
<P>
Under the Geneva Conventions, the ICRC has the right to make
further visits to the POW for as long as he is detained.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav prisoner, a lieutenant aged about 20, was
reportedly captured in Kosovo by the rebel forces Kosovo
Liberation Army on the night of April 13-14.
</P>
<P>
He was subsequently delivered to the Albanian government and
then delivered to U.S. custody in northern Albania and flown to
Tirana. He was being treated as a prisoner of war.
</P>
<P>
He is the first Yugoslav captive to be held by NATO forces
since they began air strikes on Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
The three U.S. soldiers in Serb captivity for the past three
weeks have not yet been visited by the ICRC. The ICRC spokesman
said the Geneva-based body was working on trying to obtain
clearance for a visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
