<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Swimming Sets Low-key Olympic Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAQING, NORTHEAST CHINA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese
Swimming Association (CSA) has set a surprisingly low-key target
for its swimmers at 2000 Olympic Games, but it is vigorouly
pushing forward a well-schemed training program which will tune
the swimmers up for an expectedly heated Olympic competitions in
next year's Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
The national swimming association's medal target for Sydney
requires the country's representatives to win one gold medal from
the women's events and one medal of any color in the men's
disciplines.
</P>
<P>
Sports observers believed that such an expectation was mainly
based on Chinese swimmers' poor performance at the 1996 Olympic
Games -- one gold, three silver and two bronze medals, all from
women's events -- and fairly low world rankings last year.
</P>
<P>
CSA officials admmitted that China is lagging considerably
behind such swimming powers as the United States, Australia,
Germany and Russia. "China faces a very serious situation in its
preparations for the 2000 Olympic Games," said a leading CSA
official.
</P>
<P>
But the estimation did not stop the national association from
carrying out its three-stage, nationwide program starting next
month and taking a reformed formula in the selection of Olympic
swimmers.
</P>
<P>
All of China's qualified Olympic swimmers are required to tune
up for the Sydney Games in Beijing-based CSA training camp, except
for an expectedly small number of swimmers, who, once approved by
CSA, will take training sessions out of the Chinese capital for a
certain period of time.
</P>
<P>
But priority of the preparations is obviously focused on
bringning to Sydney a "clean" squad. Absolutely no drugs, at any
costs even including hopes of gold medals, a top-ranking official
had so required.
</P>
<P>
Chinese swimmers are keen on rebuilding in Sydney their image
compromised ever since some Chinese swimmers were tested positive
for drugs in the 1994 Asian Games in Hiroshima, Japan.
</P>
<P>
Bringing all the qualified Olymic swimmers to Beijing will have
a double-edged function. Better facilities and accommodation at
the CSA camp will easier bring swimmers to the peak form. And a
special task force set up last year and backed by a group of top-
class sports medical professionals and sophistigated research gear
is set to provide timely, high-tech assistance to the elite
athletes.
</P>
<P>
The group has also to guarantee the Olympic swimmers healthy
and drugs-free. Doping tests are compulsory and blood tests have
been added even before the short-course world championships
earlier this month in Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
