<HEADLINE> IMF Used by Westerners to Punish "Unfriendly" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) is being used by some western governments as an instrument
to effect political changes in countries not popular with the big
nations, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe has said.
</P>
<P>
He told the Sunday Mail Saturday that the Bretton Woods
institute had lost its orientation completely. "Here in Zimbabwe
we have had more years without it than with it and I don't see any
reason why we can't turn our back to it."
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said, "But the World Bank, unless it proves to be
exactly like the IMF monstrous creature. I think we should remain
associated with it because we can point to very good developmental
results."
</P>
<P>
He cited various programs that had been assisted by the World
Bank which had become a source of resources that the people used
such as dams, electricity, roads and municipal houses, among
others.
</P>
<P>
The IMF on the other hand has been dilly-dallying with the
Zimbabwean government for several years promising it balance of
payments support only to come up with new demands, he said.
</P>
<P>
Several "high level" delegations have been sent to Zimbabwe
from Washington to evaluate the country's progress in implementing
economic reforms, he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite meeting most of its demands, the IMF has refused to
release the funds, he noted. 
</P>
