<HEADLINE> Jordanian High-tech Professionals Lured Into U.S., Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 1 8 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Jordanian high-tech
professionals have been lured into the United States and Canada for
better jobs and wages every year, the semi-official Jordan Times
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The majority of emigrants to the U.S. and Canada held degrees in
computer programming, graphics and animation, software developing
and engineering in civil, mechanical and electronic fields, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The number of immigrant visas issued in Jordan for the U.S. were
3,683 in 1996, 3,620 in 1997 and 2,922 in 1998, said a spokesman for
the U.S. Embassy in Amman.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed most of the visas his embassy issued in 1998
were family reunion visas and only 3 percent were employment
immigrant visas.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian embassy in Amman issued 508 immigration visas to
Jordanians in 1998, the Jordan Times said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the would-be immigrant workers in the U.S. and Canada
were hoping for better jobs and higher wages, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Economic recession in the desert kingdom and political
uncertainty in the Middle East also prompted Jordanian professionals
to look for a better future in North America, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan registered a negative economic growth in 1998, and estimates
over the unemployment rate of the country ranged from 16 to 25
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
