<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bao Zheng Remembered in Central China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Kaifeng, a historical and
cultural city in central China's Henan Province, has decided to
arrange a number of activities this month to mark the 1,000th
anniversary of the birth of Bao Zheng, an ancient Chinese famed as
an honest and upright official.
</P>
<P>
These activities include different symposiums and drama
episodes. The city government of Kaifeng has also planned to
earmark 28 million yuan to rebuild the office building of Bao
Zheng.
</P>
<P>
Bao Zheng (Bao Gong), who was born in April 999 A.D. in present-
day Hefei City of Anhui Province, used to be the magistrate of the
capital Kaifeng in the period of Northern Song Dynasty (A.D. 960-
1127). He was highly esteemed for his strictness in upholding
justice in performing his duty and unyielding to the misconduct of
the powerful officials. Bao died in 1062.
</P>
<P>
Bao Zheng, eulogized in Chinese literary works in many forms
through ages, has always been presented as a person with a black
face suggesting the impartial and upright feature of the ancient
Chinese official, though Bao was actually an handsome man with
fair complexion according to historical records. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990418.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
