<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Wrong Policies Cause Fall of Vajpayee Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The wrong policies pursued by
India's 13-month-old Vajpayee multi-party coalition government
were the main cause of its own collapse in a vote of confidence in
the Lower House of Parliament Saturday, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The major challenge facing the Vajpayee government when it came
into power on March 19 last year was poverty alleviation and
further economic reforms needed to achieve fast economic growth in
the country.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, one-third of the country's
population are living below the poverty line and over a half of
the population are illiterate. Find solutions to these problems
should have been the new government's main preoccupation.
</P>
<P>
The government, however, had focused its attention on
development of nuclear and missile weapons. In its last year's
budget, nuclear and space development funds had increased sharply,
by 67 percent and 62 percent respectively. The then Finance
Minister Jashwant Singh has said defense expenditure could be
increased any time if necessary.
</P>
<P>
The Vajpayee government conducted five underground nuclear
tests in May last year, causing widespread concern and drawing
condemnation both at home and abroad. Just days before its ouster,
the government test-fired short-range and intermediate ballistic
missiles with ranges of 50 to over 2,000 km, prompting India's
major rival Pakistan to follow suit, intensifying an armed race in
the South Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Both the Bharatiya Janata Party and the Vajpayee government had
made a lot of promises to the public during the general election
last year and since then, but few of them had materialized.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, both the industry and the public were also deeply
disgruntled with the fact that the country's economy showed no
sign of recovery while the fiscal deficit and inflation were
rising. Crime rates are rising fast, and communal forces again
ignited racial and religious hatred flames with some of lower
caste and minority people becoming victims of such hatred.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Vajpayee coalition was strife-laden and its
allies with various ideologies and interests had never ceased
infightings among themselves. Many charged that what they really
cared about were their own affairs and benefits, but never the
people's welfare and the country's progress.
</P>
<P>
The government had spent so much time on infighting, but little
time on how to run the country well, and more and more people have
become disillusioned with it, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
With the collapse of the Vajpayee administration, the Congress
Party, the biggest opposition in Parliament, is expected to form a
new government on its own with the support of other opposition
parties from outside or to form a Congress-led coalition
government with some of opposition parties joining it.
</P>
<P>
Yet any form of government will face new difficulties and
challenges, as the strength of the new government is balanced with
new opposition parties, who are expected to fight back soon.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the new government would face similar problems as the
Vajpayee government had, as Congress and its supporting parties
hold different views and their priorities could also be different.
</P>
<P>
The industry and the public are now eager to see a stable
government formed as soon as possible and the Finance Bill and
other bills adopted so as to put the country's economic
development back on track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990418.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern China Province's Foreign Trade Dropping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province's exports
and imports continued to fall in the first quarter of this year,
but exports of private companies were up.
</P>
