<HEADLINE> Mugabe Castigates U.S. Bombing in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
has castigated the United States for bombing in Kosovo, saying it
is "wielding power" in the world.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Sunday Mail on the eve of
the country' s 19th independence anniversary (on April 18), Mugabe
expressed outrage at how the Americans arbitrarily interfered with
the affairs of other sovereign countries in complete disregard of
the U.N Security Council.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The Americans have become the world's Titan and in
the absence of the Soviet Union you can see how they are wielding
power across the world and in some cases in a very reckless
manner."
</P>
<P>
"To carry out those bombings arbitrarily in Kosovo is highly
objectionable in light of the fact that we have the U.N. Security
Council that is charged with the responsibility of enforcing
international security and stability and a matter like that should
be a concern of and for the U.N. security organ," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But no! America decides that they want to bomb a particularly
country and willy-nilly. Sheepish Britain follows wherever
American goes on these bloody adventures," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president said that he supports the Americans to fight
terrorism, But America itself , in fact, use terrorism or such
methods to get rid of leaders they do not like, even if those
leaders have been elected democratically by their own people, so
that they put leaders they like.
</P>
<P>
"This has, in my view, to be raised at the highest
international levels such as the U.N. and we, as the Non-Aligned
Movement, must consider this matter at our summits as frankly and
blatantly as we can and register our objection," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In light of this fact, we have to improve on our defenses and
peace strategies. It means we have to build up our defence and
security forces and strengthen our intelligence services whereas
it would have been better to deploy our resources in improving the
social status of our people," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He noted, "We now have to ensure that peace and stability and
the security of our nation are given adequate resources."
</P>
</TEXT>
