<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2,000-Year Old Tombs Found in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
found more than 300 ancient tombs, which can be dated back to the
Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-220), in Tangxian County of Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists also unearthed 50 pieces of historical
relics from the tombs, including pottery, bronze articles, jade
ornament and coins.
</P>
<P>
Among the relics, a pottery figurine of a young woman is
considered to be one of the rarest of the finds, with a beautiful
design depicting her hair-style and dress.
</P>
<P>
An archaeologist commented that the tomb site was used as an
ancient public graveyard in the period, with some just coffins
buried in pits and others in brick chambers.
</P>
<P>
The tombs and relics will provide valuable clues for
archaeological research on religion and the finery of the Han
Dynasty, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
