<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of the Macao SAR Basic Law (37) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 37 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
How many tiers of courts will the MSAR establish? Who will
appoint or remove judges for the MSAR's Court of Final Appeals?
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law grants the MSAR independent judicial power and
power of final adjudication once Macao is returned to China. MSAR
courts will have complete and exclusive power of adjudication over
all cases in the region, with the exception of matters of acts of
State such as national defense and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law provides for a three-tiered court system --
primary, intermediate courts and the Court of Final Appeals, to
ensure a high degree of independent judicial power in the MSAR.
</P>
<P>
The power of final adjudication will be vested in the MSAR's
Court of Final Appeals.
</P>
<P>
Judges on the MSAR's Court of Final Appeals, just as for other
courts, will be appointed by the Chief Executive on the
recommendation of an independent commission composed of local
judges, lawyers and prominent citizens.
</P>
<P>
A Court of Final Appeals judge can only be removed due to an
inability to perform duties or for behavior incompatible with the
post.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive will decide on the removal of a Court of
Final Appeals judge based on the suggestions of a review committee
consisting of members of the MSAR's Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law further stipulates that appointments and removals
of the President and judges for the Court of Final Appeals will be
reported to the National People's Congress Standing Committee for
the record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990418.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Kiefer Wins Japan Open Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Nicolas Kiefer of Germany captured
his second career title by beating Wayne Ferreira of South Africa
at the Japan Open tennis tournament here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old German, who scored his first ATP title at
Toulouse in September 1997, fought for a 7-6 (7/4), 7-5 victory in
only his fourth career final.
</P>
<P>
"I'm here for the first time and I won the tournament. I'm very
satisfied with my play today," said Kiefer who won the title with
low but accurate strokes and a sudden array of hard-hit shots.
</P>
<P>
After exchanging breaks in the second and seventh games of the
first set, Ferreira hit a service return winner to trail 4-5 in
the tie-breaker which Kiefer eventually won by making Ferreira
commit errors twice.
</P>
<P>
Ferreira, playing his first final in three years, changed the
rhythm and the speed and again came back from service break down
to even it at five-all.
</P>
<P>
But his chances of winning his first title since August 1996
were bleak as he hit a backhand shot into the net at 15-40 to go
down 5-6, giving Kiefer a second chance to serve out for the match.
</P>
<P>
The victory brought Kiefer close to breaking inside the top 20
for the first time in his career. 
</P>
</TEXT>
