<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of the Macao SAR Basic Law (38) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 38 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
How should the MSAR conduct judicial assistance with other
parts of China and foreign countries?
</P>
<P>
Judicial assistance refers to instances when a judicial
department provides facilities and assistance to a department from
a different jurisdiction, including transfers of fugitives,
delivery of judicial documents, summoning witnesses, and
acceptance and implementation of outside judicial decisions.
</P>
<P>
Article 93 in the Basic Law stipulates that the MSAR will
maintain judicial relations with and render assistance to judicial
departments in other parts of China through consultations and in
accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
Judicial assistance between the MSAR and other parts of China
by nature involves local assistance.
</P>
<P>
Article 94 in the Basic Law stipulates that the Central
People's Government will assist and grant authorization for the
MSAR to make appropriate reciprocal judicial assistance
arrangements with foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Judicial assistance between the MSAR, a local administrative
region of China, and foreign countries is by nature an
international act directly related to foreign affairs. Therefore,
the MSAR must request assistance and obtain authorization from the
Central People's Government in accordance with the principle of
State sovereignty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
