<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: S. Leone Rebels Expected to Hold Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Sierra leone rebels are expected to
hold peace talks with the President Tejan Kabbah government in a
bid to end the nine-year civil war in the West African country.
</P>
<P>
Final preparations for a travel of jailed rebel leader Foday
Sankoh to Togo were ready on Friday when the United Nations lifted
the travel ban on him, a day after the Sierra Leone appeal court
agreed to release him temporarily.
</P>
<P>
A Sierra Leone government spokesman said Friday that Sankoh
would be flown to Togo on Saturday accompanied by U.N.
representatives and was expected to consult his followers on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Following the face-to-face meeting with his followers, Sankoh
would hold peace talks with the Kabbah government to try to bring
peace to the war- ravaged country.
</P>
<P>
The decision to release him and his travel to Togo for meeting
with his followers are described as the most important step
towards peace in the West African country for several years.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh has been in detention since he was picked up on arms
offences in Nigeria in early 1997 and was sentenced to death last
October as his Revolutionary United Front (RUF) briefly shared
power in Freetown with renegade army officers between May 1997 and
February 1998.
</P>
<P>
The RUF invaded Freetown early last January, and some 6,000
people were reportedly killed in the ensuing violence between the
West African peace- keeping force of ECOMOG and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The government of President Kabbah welcomed the appeal court's
decision, calling Sankoh's travel to Togo "a mission of national
importance" and " another important milestone in the peace
process" in the country.
</P>
<P>
Since the RUF took up arms in 1991, at least 20,000 people have
been killed in Sierra Leone where almost every infrastructure,
especially outside the capital, has been crippled by the war.
</P>
<P>
The Togo meeting is scheduled to be held in Kara, the
birthplace of President Gnassingbe Eyadema, current chairman of
the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), who is to
host the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The eventual meeting is seen as a crucial precursor to
full-scale peace talks between the rebel RUF and President Kabbah
government, coming at a time when Sierra leone's security
situation is precarious.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said Thursday that Kambia on the border with
Guinea in the north was now free of rebels while the northern town
of Makeni, the country's third largest city, remains a rebel
stronghold.
</P>
<P>
In the east, the sources said, the rebels still control
Kailahun which is the main base of the rebel movement while the
Freetown peninsula remain in the control of the ECOMOG troops.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigerian Chief of Defence Staff Air Marshal Al-Amin
Daggash announced Thursday in capital Abuja that the ECOMOG would
begin to withdraw the 15,000-strong troops in Sierra leone later
this year.
</P>
<P>
Defence chiefs of countries with troops in Sierra Leone ended a
one-day extraordinary meeting in Abuja on Thursday with a call on
ECOWAS member countries to support the on-going rebuilding of the
Sierra leone armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's former army, which sided with the RUF, was
demobilized by ECOMOG last year when it reinstated the
democratically elected President Kabbah after he was overthrown by
the military junta.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to rebuild the army, 500 officer cadets have been
sent for training in Nigeria while the rest of the 5,000-strong
army is being trained locally by Nigerian and British officers.
</P>
<P>
Observers said that the Kabbah government is desperate for a
peace pact with the rebels during the peace talks next week.
</P>
<P>
Unless the talks succeed, the capital city of Freetown could be
laid open within weeks to a new rebel assault, they added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
