<HEADLINE> Zhu: Talks With Canadian Prime Minister Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CALGARY, Canada, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier
Zhu Rongji said Saturday that his talks with Canadian Prime
Minister Jean Chretien in Ottawa Friday were frank, friendly and
fruitful, which promoted understanding and increased common ground
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a dinner hosted by Minister of Justice and Attorney
General of Canada Anne Mclellan, Zhu said he came to Canada to
implement the common ground reached by Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and Chretien during the former's state visit to Canada in
1997. "I believe we have accomplished a lot," he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhu arrived in St. John's on April 14 to start his seven-day
official visit to Canada following his successful visit to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of his visit is to deepen understanding, expand
common ground, enhance friendship and promote cooperation so as to
advance the 21st century-oriented China-Canada partnership of all-
round cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Canada is willing to see China's access to the World Trade
Organization (WTO), Zhu said, adding that China's WTO membership
will give a bigger market for Canadian entrepreneurs and business
people.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Zhu said both the United States and Canada have
resolutely supported China's entry into the WTO and China's
negotiations with the two countries are near completion.
</P>
<P>
It has been 13 years since negotiations started on China's
resumption of the General Agreement on Trade Tariff (GATT)
membership and later on its access to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said China's entry into the WTO can not only widen Sino-
Canadian economic and trade ties but also improve the trade
imbalance between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that more and more Canadians will do business and
invest in China so as to further promote bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Mclellan, who welcomed Zhu's visit, said relations between
Canada and China are established on the basis of mutual respect
and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
She expressed her hope that the two countries will increase
mutual visits to further enlarge bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Zhu arrived here from Toronto Saturday afternoon to continue
his visit, a return one to Chretien. This is his first trip to
Canada in the capacity as Chinese premier. 
</P>
