<HEADLINE> Bangladesh President Urges Parties to Reach Understanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi President Shahabuddin
Ahmed has urged the country's ruling and opposition parties to
make concessions to reach an understanding on political issues,
the New Nations newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Not confrontation, compromise is essential. Everybody needs to
give some concessions and shift from one's respective stances to
create an understanding," Ahmed was quoted as speaking at a
discussion on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"But in our country, no politician or party will ever confess
their faults so long alive, never budge an inch. There will be no
recognition even if the other party did a good job," he said.
</P>
<P>
As people are the source of all power, he said, it "can't be
possible to sail through election all the time by misleading,
deceiving or bluffing them."
</P>
<P>
He deplored that although 28 years had passed since the
country's independence, efforts to fulfill the people's basic
rights were yet to succeed. "It is the most urgent tasks of all to
make a united effort disregarding party to resolve national
problems. It requires a consensus by all political parties on
major national issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But in lieu of unity, we now see extreme disunity, serious
conflict and confrontational politics," he said, adding that the
cornerstone of democracy was tolerance and cooperation between the
government and the opposition for resolving the country's
fundamental problems.
</P>
<P>
"This is unfortunate that such an environment has not been
created in our country yet. The main feature of the government and
the opposition is to blame each other, abuse each other in harsh
language and invoke the bitter past all the time," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president said the basic problems would not be solved by
abusing each other or shifting all the blames to others.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible to make error in governing the country. But
rule or administration is not the monopoly of any individual or
party... The lesson of history is that a good ruler first detects
his own mistake and corrects himself before finding fault with
others," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is our misfortune that in our country no leaders confess
their own mistakes. Their motto: our party is right and our
actions unchangeable. Whatever others do is wrong. Our party is
patriotic, others traitors," he said.
</P>
<P>
"All will have to work unitedly so that economic development
work does not suffer. The country's interest will take precedence
over personal interest and the path of vendetta must be replaced
by mutual understanding," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has been gripped by political uncertainty in recent
years. The ruling and the opposition have often tried to shift
blames to each other for any failure in governing the country, by
confronting each other both in parliament and on the street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
