<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Gulf War Victims to Get More Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Commission for
Compensation (UNCC) will give an additional 45 million U.S.
dollars to Sri Lankan expatriates who lost their jobs due to the
1990-91 Gulf War, officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This will be the fifth time Sri Lankan Gulf War victims are to
receive compensation.
</P>
<P>
A total of 18,000 Sri Lankan expatriates will receive
compensation this time, Sri Lankan Foreign Employment Bureau
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said about 90,000 Sri Lankan workers had returned
from Kuwait since August 2, 1990, when Iraq invaded Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
After the war, the United Nations established a special
commission on compensation known as the UNCC, to pay an allowance
to those who were compelled to return.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has received four installments so far -- 48.8 million
U.S. dollars in December 1996, 15.9 million dollars in March 1997,
33 million dollars and 48 million dollars in April and August last
year.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the sixth and final installment will be
received soon, sometime in May this year. 
