<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Caribbean Basin States Hope for Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTO DOMINGO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- More than 20 leaders of
government of the Caribbean basin discussed Saturday its economic
integration in the American continent, in the Second Association
of Caribbean States (ACS) Summit.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, attended by the leaders of small islands in the
Caribbean east and Mexico, Colombia, Venezuela and Cuba, ended
Saturday with the signing of a document that basically contains
political declarations and intentions of regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The ACS member states have a population of more than 200
million and a 500-billion gross domestic product. Leaders were
proposing to set a regional tariff system to prepare for the Free
Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA) and its target date of 2005.
</P>
<P>
There were also expected Cuba to join the FTAA negotiations,
calling the United States to end its nearly 40-year-long embargo
on the island, especially the Helms-Burton law against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said they will promote the Caribbean's vital
tourism industry, which created jobs for the one fifth of their
population and earned 18 billion dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Dominican President Leonel Fernandez, the host of the summit,
said in the first working session that the United States must
extend the benefits of the free trade agreement in textile matters
to the Caribbean, and the Lome Accord with the European Union (EU)
should be extended for 10 years more. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
