<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Raps Tokyo Governor's Anti-China Ravings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 18 (Xinhua) -- A leading Chinese newspaper
warned Sunday that the anti-China remarks by newly-elected Tokyo
governor Shintaro Ishihara are both shocking and deserve
condemnation.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Japanese media on April 12, Ishihara
flagrantly attacked the Chinese government and its policy on Tibet
and uttered provocative words on the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
In a signed article entitled "Unpopular Ravings", the People's
Daily said that it was not the first time that Ishihara made anti-
China remarks. In the early 1990s, he flatly denied the crimes
committed by Japanese aggressors in the Nanjing massacre, saying
that the criminal act was a "fabrication". In the just-ended
gubernatorial election, he again defended Japan's crimes of
aggression. All these remarks attempting to reverse historical
verdicts were strongly criticized by both Chinese and Japanese
public opinions.
</P>
<P>
The People's Daily article said: "The fact that a public office
holder repeatedly made such anti-China ravings will inevitably
have very bad political implications and cause serious
consequences."
</P>
<P>
The article noted that Ishihara's understanding of China and
historical issues not only is totally wrong but also lacks common
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
It is the choice of the Chinese people that the Communist Party
of China has been leading them in building a prosperous,
democratic, civilized and modernized socialist country, the
article said. "How could Ishihara, as a foreigner, be in a
position to vilify the fact?"
</P>
<P>
It is a historical fact that Tibet has been an integral part of
China since the ancient time, the article said. "On what basis
could he claim that Tibet was 'annexed' by China?"
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan issue is a major issue of principle that concerns
China's internal affair and sovereignty, a position that has been
accepted by the Japanese government, the article went on. "If
Ishihara disregards the Japanese government's solemn commitment
and engages in 'one China, one Taiwan' activities in his capacity
as the Tokyo governor, he would badly hurt the feelings of the 1.
25 billion Chinese people and seriously undermine the Sino-
Japanese relations. The consequences would be ghastly to
contemplate."
</P>
<P>
The article said, "The friendly relations between China and
Japan are hard won and their further growth allows no interference
whatsoever." It added that any remarks and actions against the
historical trend of Sino-Japanese friendship will certainly come
to no good end.
</P>
<P>
"We advise Mr. Ishihara to give an overriding consideration to
the Sino-Japanese friendly relations and the regional stability
within his tenure of office and to refrain from making any more
remarks that will undermine the fundamental interests of the
Chinese and Japanese people and damage the relations between the
two countries." the article concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990418.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo-bound Munitions Intercepted in Macedonia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Macedonian Interior Minister Pavle
Trajanov announced Saturday in Skopje that Macedonian police have
intercepted a large quantity of munitions bound for Kosovo from
Albania.
</P>
<P>
The munitions, found in a tractor hauling a trailer in Lojane
village, totaled 308 pieces. Among them were rifles, submachine
guns, automatic rifles, grenade launchers and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
More munitions were discovered during follow-up searches in the
village.
</P>
<P>
Police said the munitions were being smuggled from Albania to
reach the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
The case was only one in a series of similar weaponry smuggling
via Macedonia since conflicts broke out in the Serb province in
February last year.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia, including Kosovo, is under weaponry embargo imposed
by the international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
