<HEADLINE> At Least 20 Killed in clash in East Timor, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 18 (Xinhua) -- At least 20 people were killed
following a clash on Saturday between pro-integration and
pro-independence groups in Dili, capital of Indonesia's East
Timor, national newspapers reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Dili police chief Col. Timbul Silaen said 12 bodies were found
in the house of pro-independence figure Manuel Carrascalao, the
brother of former East Timor governor Mario Viegas Carrascalao.
</P>
<P>
Five others were found in the house of David Ximenes, deputy
chairman of the National Council of Resistance of East Timor
(CNRT), an umbrella group for the pro-independence movement. In
addition, three people were killed on streets in clashes between
pro-independence supporters and the pro-Indonesia militia.
</P>
<P>
But Mario Viegas Carrascalao said about 30 people were killed
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that pro-Indonesia militia went on the rampage
after holding a rally in Dili on Saturday morning. Around 1,500
militiamen drove round the city's deserted streets in a convoy of
some 25 trucks, firing in the air and attacking the homes of known
pro-independence activists.
</P>
<P>
Some opened fire and pelted rocks at the home of Manuel
Carrascalao. There were about 150 refugees in the house.
</P>
<P>
Scores of pro-integration East Timorese youths ransacked the
offices of The Suara Timor Timur (The Voice of East Timor)
newspaper, which they accused of biased reporting against their
cause.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's violence came after weeks of bloodshed from fighting
among various pro- and anti-independence groups as well as the
Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
It was the biggest show of force by anti-independence fighters
since a new wave of violence hit the troubled territory a few
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor, with a population
of some 800,000 and an area of 15,000 sq. km, was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
On January 27 this year, the Indonesian government announced it
was ready to release East Timor if the alternative to provide
wider autonomy was refused by the people in the region and the
international community.
</P>
<P>
Violence has heightened since the announcement.
</P>
<P>
As part of efforts to find a peaceful solution to the thorny
issue, Indonesia, Portugal and the United Nations have agreed to
hold a U.N.-supervised ballot on autonomy in East Timor in July,
one month after Indonesia's planned elections on June 7.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Affairs Minister Ali Alatas is expected to
present his government's final autonomy proposal during a two-day
meeting with his Portuguese counterpart Jaime Gama in New York on
April 21.
</P>
<P>
However, the Indonesian government rejected mounting calls for
some kind of U.N. presence in East Timor, even as critics charged
it with failing to arrest the rising violence in the territory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
