<HEADLINE> Salamander Fries Returned To Nature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 18 (Xinhua) -- Environmentalists in the city of
Lanzhou, the capital of China's Gansu Province in northwest China,
recently returned 30,000 salamander fries that had been stolen by
smugglers back to nature.
</P>
<P>
They were believed to have been stolen from somewhere in the
southern part of China.
</P>
<P>
The environmentalists first put 10,000 of the fries into a
stream in the Xinglongshan Nature Reserve, 30 kilometers south of
Lanzhou, but stopped when they saw that the small fish looked
uncomfortable. The remaining 20,000 are now being raised in a 0.13-
hectare pond in the nature reserve.
</P>
<P>
Local fishery department officials say that the small
salamanders may be moved to other places if they do not adjust to
the environment and climate in the reserve.
</P>
<P>
The theft of the salamanders is still under investigation,
according to local judicial sources. The salamander is considered
an endangered species and is protected by the State. It makes a
crying sound like that of an infant in the evening and has been
given the Chinese nickname "wawa yu", or "baby fish". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
